## Diagnosis

`crimes` flagged **`crime_00023` — "Sync I/O in Hot Path"** on `src/api/files.ts`, severity `low` but confidence `0.9`. Quoting the evidence verbatim:

> - `` `existsSync` @L12 in `loadPlanSchema` (domain function) ``
> - `` `statSync` @L13 in `loadPlanSchema` (domain function) ``
> - `` `readFileSync` @L15 in `loadPlanSchema` (domain function) ``
> - `lines: 12, 13, 15`
> - `` swap for the async variant (`readFile`, `writeFile`, `exec`, …) and `await` it ``

Each invocation of `loadPlanSchema()` blocks the Node event loop three times: an `existsSync` stat, an explicit `statSync`, and the `readFileSync` slurp of `SCHEMA_PATH`. Under concurrent load every in-flight request waits behind the disk read of whichever request got there first — exactly the p99/event-loop-lag signature you described.

## Smallest async migration

Preserve the export name and arity; only the return type widens from `unknown` to `Promise<unknown>` (the minimum change required to release the loop). Drop `existsSync` + `statSync` entirely — they're a TOCTOU-prone preflight that `readFile` already subsumes via its error path.

```ts
import { readFile } from "node:fs/promises";

export async function loadPlanSchema(): Promise<unknown> {
  try {
    const contents = await readFile(SCHEMA_PATH, "utf8");
    if (contents.length === 0) return null;
    return JSON.parse(contents);
  } catch (err) {
    if ((err as NodeJS.ErrnoException).code === "ENOENT") return null;
    throw err;
  }
}
```

Why this is the minimum:
- One `await readFile` replaces all three blocking syscalls — no separate `exists`/`stat` round-trips.
- The `ENOENT → null` branch reproduces the old `existsSync → null` semantics.
- `contents.length === 0` reproduces the old `stat.size === 0 → null` short-circuit without a second syscall.
- Callers update from `loadPlanSchema()` to `await loadPlanSchema()` — the name, parameters, and null-on-missing contract are unchanged.
